<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The move could help smooth the path for MGM to join the stock markets by providing an exit for a notoriously outspoken investor. Mr. Icahn bought into the film studioâs debt to try to force the company into a merger with Lionsgate Films, a campaign that failed.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">M.G.M. instead struck agreements with a number of creditors that allowed the company to file for a prepackaged bankruptcy, which shortened its stay in Chapter 11 protection. Under the terms of that filing, the film studioâs creditors essentially took control, making Mr. Icahn one of the companyâs biggest shareholders. A spokeswoman for MGM declined to comment.<br /><span class="elsewhere"><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2012/07/31/m-g-m-said-to-plan-a-buyout-of-icahns-stake/">DealBook &#187;</a></span></p>
